&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Pre-Bundled Scripts&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Not just that, but they also supply so many pre-configured scripts that make harder tasks on other distros so damn simple, it&amp;rsquo;s not even funny. They even supply an image with the &lt;strong&gt;nVidia&lt;/strong&gt; or &lt;strong&gt;AMD&lt;/strong&gt; drivers baked it and pre-configured for you so you don&amp;rsquo;t have to lift a finger.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
  &lt;figure&gt;
    &lt;img class=&#34;my-0 rounded-md&#34; loading=&#34;lazy&#34; src=&#34;https://i.imgur.com/qNeqmIG.png&#34; alt=&#34;ujust&#34; /&gt;
    
  &lt;/figure&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Stability and Immunability&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Also, the fact that it&amp;rsquo;s so stable with truly &lt;em&gt;almost&lt;/em&gt; zero-maintenance needed by you the user is a &lt;em&gt;Huge&lt;/em&gt; benefit. Especially that it uses &lt;em&gt;rpm-ostree&lt;/em&gt;. And that it&amp;rsquo;s immune to any mistakes you might make, is so awesome. If you break the system just reboot select an older &lt;em&gt;snapshot&lt;/em&gt; and you are back up and running. However one can still break it, but you really have to try lol.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;They even supply an image for us devs out there with all the tools we might need to be productive out the box. I mean wow, could there &lt;em&gt;be&lt;/em&gt; any more handholding ?&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;h3 class=&#34;relative group&#34;&gt;The Downsides (No Dealbreakers) 
    &lt;div id=&#34;the-downsides-no-dealbreakers&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
    
&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Too Much Cruft ?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Which brings me to the only &lt;em&gt;Big&lt;/em&gt; downside, which is in my humble opinion, that it has way too much out the box, even the simple version. I get it, it aims to be as out of one&amp;rsquo;s way as possible letting us be more productive, while I agree with this, it tends to target a smaller audience. Coz not everyone wants or needs everything it provides. I mean we don&amp;rsquo;t even get to choose what we want out the box, ending up having to remove the cruft we do not need. Maybe that&amp;rsquo;s more of a &lt;strong&gt;Fedora&lt;/strong&gt; limitation I do not know.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Laziness / No Self-Reliance&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Now this is much less of an issue, more of an obervation, but if I have learned something during my Distro Maintaining days, it&amp;rsquo;s that doing too much for the user out the box, will make them both lazy and will end up too dependent on us devs/maintainers. While I can&amp;rsquo;t speak for the team behind &lt;strong&gt;uBlue&lt;/strong&gt;, it&amp;rsquo;s just impossible to satisfy everyone.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;No Freedom To Tinker&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The other downside to this whole idea of &lt;strong&gt;Atomic&lt;/strong&gt; distros, is that, if you were a tinkerer like me, who loves to mess with the system, modify core functionalities, you simply can&amp;rsquo;t. As such you will be &lt;em&gt;heavily&lt;/em&gt; relying on &lt;strong&gt;Flatpaks&lt;/strong&gt;. It&amp;rsquo;s not a big deal though, since this project wasn&amp;rsquo;t meant to be used that way, so am not gonna be docking it any points for that.&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;h3 class=&#34;relative group&#34;&gt;Would I recommend it ? 
    &lt;div id=&#34;would-i-recommend-it-&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
    
&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In conclusion, I will say, this is my opinion, and that you should take it with a huge grain of salt. I am a tinkerer, a not so ordinary user so to speak. And I have only been using it a day as of the writing of this post.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;But yes, of ourse I would &lt;strong&gt;Highly&lt;/strong&gt; recommend you at least give it a try. Just make sure to select the version that works best for you. Be it &lt;strong&gt;AMD&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;nVidia&lt;/strong&gt;, or the &lt;strong&gt;Dev/DX&lt;/strong&gt; version.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Just make sure you know that you will not be able to tinker much with it, the way you would be able to with the likes of &lt;strong&gt;Arch&lt;/strong&gt; or the likes.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;As for me, nope it will not replace my daily driver, &lt;strong&gt;ArchLinux&lt;/strong&gt;, nothing will, I prefer my freedom for tinkering with the system. I was just curious as to what the deal was with all the &lt;strong&gt;Atomic&lt;/strong&gt; distros out there is all.&lt;/p&gt;
